  "prompt": "Will there be a sufficient space for rough work in offline mode of JEE?",
  "response": "In the offline mode of the Joint Entrance Examination (JEE), also known as the JEE Main Pen and Paper mode, students are typically given a question paper along with an answer sheet (OMR sheet). Traditionally, the question paper does include some space for rough work, although it might be limited. \n\nFor extensive rough work, students often need to use the spaces provided in the margins or at the back of the question paper. It's important to manage this space efficiently. However, the exact amount of space available can vary from year to year based on the exam guidelines set by the examination authorities.\n\nIf you're concerned about having enough space for rough work, here are a few tips:\n\n1. **Practice Efficiency**: During preparation, practice being concise with your calculations and problem-solving approaches to use the available space effectively.\n   \n2. **Organize Tasks**: Try to layout your rough work in a clear and organized manner so you can refer back to it easily if needed.\n\n3. **Stay Updated**: Keep an eye on the official JEE information bulletin or announcements from the National Testing Agency (NTA), as they might provide specific details about the examination format and guidelines.\n\nRemember to follow any specific instructions given in the exam regarding rough work to ensure compliance with the examination rules.",
